  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrated (HIV Effect) Mitigation and Positive Action for Community Transformation (IMPACT)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Care Group Model, Community-Led Complementary Feeding and Learning Sessions, Community-Integrated Management of Childhood Illnesses, Village Savings and Loans, Birth Registration, Interactive Education on Child Rights, HIV Testing and Counselling, Community-Based pre-ART Services</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Children ages 0-17, OVC Caregivers, Children Living with or at Risk of HIV/AIDS</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">IMPACT is a four year, USAID-funded project whose goal is to improve the wellbeing of 58,017 orphans and vulnerable children (OVC) and to improve access to treatment and care for 41,505 people living with HIV (PLHIV). Through Care Groups, OVC caregivers are provided with on-the-job and group-based training sessions in basic child health procedures, child protection, food preservation, and food preparation. In FY12, these Care Groups empowered 1,339 caregivers by allowing them the opportunity to participate in peer-to-peer education in maternal and child health with a focus on infant and young child  feeding; water, sanitation and hygiene; reproductive health; and HIV/AIDS prevention. Caregivers involved in PCI&#x2019;s Care Groups have shown substantial changes in behavior, resulting in health gains for the target population of orphans and vulnerable children. PCI also assisted with child abuse and exploitation response, promoted primary school retention, and increased financial and academic support to participating children. By supporting the integration of Nutrition Assessment Counseling and Support, IMPACT supports the referral of malnourished children and adults to nutrition rehabilitation units. Vulnerable households are educated about and encouraged to participate in village savings and loans groups (VS&amp;amp;L). Additionally, communities are educated and encouraged to participate in HIV counselling and testing, and local government offices receive training providing technical support to PLHIV. In mid-2013, IMPACT began a study to assess if a Care Group methodology that focuses on fathers will impact household and community behaviors in reproductive, maternal and child health practices.</narrative>
  </description>
